CHAPTER 1 INTRODUCTION Statement of the Problem The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 was enacted primarily to address the rising drug prevalence in America. In a 1982 household survey conducted by the Office of National Drug Control Policy, rising drug use was traced among Americans. Among those 12 and over, 12.2% reported use in the past 30 days; among those 18-25,30.8% reported use in the past 30 days (Timrots & Byrne, 1995). Cocaine use, in particular, appeared so commonplace, the general public considered it an epidemic. The same study showed 3.8% of those 26 and over, and 18.2% of those 18-25 reporting monthly cocaine use during this time (Timrots & Byrne, 1995). The decade o f the 1980s was also marked by an increase in violent crimes; in 1986, there were 34.1 million estimated crimes nationally, 5.5 million of which were violent (Flanagan & Jamieson, 1988). The surge in violent crime was blamed, in part, on high drug prevalence. In 1987, there were 17,963 homicides, 4.9% were identified as drug-related (Spiess & Fallow, 2000; Timrots & Byrne, 1995). Between 31% and 36% of those arrested for crimes were under the influence of an illicit drug (Beck et al., 1993). For those who commit violent crimes, 46% reported drug use in the previous month, 28% reported being under the influence of drugs at the time o f the crime, and 12% reported committing the crime in order to get money for drugs (Beck et al., 1993). The Bureau of
1

Justice adapted the belief that, due to competition and disputes among drug dealers and consumers, drugs and violence were inextricably related (Spiess & Fallow, 2000).
Believing that tougher sanctions would discourage and reduce drug-related offenses, Congress enacted the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 which imposed mandatory minimum sentences on those in possession of illicit substances (Pub. L. 99-570,1986). Mandatory minimums were seen as a key step in reducing the supply and demand of drugs, thus eliminating the problem of drug use altogether (Eddy, 2003). If drug use was eliminated, then drug-related crimes should also be eliminated (Eddy, 2003).
Although drug use has yet to be eliminated, usage appears less today than it had been. During the 2000s, drug prevalence amongst those 12 and over steadily remained between 8% and 8.9% (Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration, 2011); cocaine use with the same population remained consistently below 1%, even decreasing throughout the decade (Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration, 2011). In 2011, monthly use among those 12 and over had declined to 8.1% (Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration, 2012); meanwhile, 0.5% of the same population report cocaine use in the past 30 days (National Institute on Drug Abuse, 2012). In 2010,21.5% of adults 18-25 report past month use of any substances, 3% report past month use of cocaine (Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration, 2011).
The impact of mandatory minimums on reducing drug-related violent crimes is questionable. In 2007, there were 14,831 homicides, and only 3.9% were identified as drug-related—1% less than what drug-related crimes had been two decades prior (Spiess

& Fallow, 2000). While this data suggests a slight reduction in drug-related crimes, it is interesting to note that drug-related homicides peaked at 6.2% in 1991--several years after the implementation o f mandatory minimums (Spiess & Fallow, 2000).
Since this policy’s implementation, drug-related arrest rates have increased dramatically. In 1982, the police made approximately 676,000 drug arrests; in 2007, the number had risen to 1.8 million arrests (Dorsey & James, 2009). While 7.4% of arrests reported to the FBI were for drug charges in 1987, 13% of arrests were for drug charges in 2007 (Dorsey & James, 2009). In 1986, only 9% of those serving time in prison were charged with a drug offense (Beck et al., 1993), but by 2003, that number had risen to 57% (Eddy, 2003).
The effect on our jails and prisons of increased drug arrests is quite clear. In the years since implementation, inmate population soared from 500,000 in 1980 (Glaze, Minton, & West, 2010) to 2.29 million in 2009 (Glaze, 2010). An estimated 70% of prison population growth is attributed to increased sentences for drug laws (Simon, 1993). Over half of those incarcerated in federal prisons were charged with drug-related crimes (Eddy, 2003; Pratt, 2009). Nearly 500,000 arrested individuals received charges subject to a mandatory minimum. In 2010 alone, nearly 16,000 people were convicted of crimes that carried a mandatory minimum penalty, incurring sentences that would leave them incarcerated anywhere from five years to life (United States Sentencing Commission, 2011). A recent financial study determined the average cost per inmate, per year at $31,286, meaning the total financial impact ranges upward of $39 billion~a heavy monetary cost for the tax-paying public (Hendrichson & Delaney, 2012).
3

By looking at the prison population, we can learn that people and communities of color are being disproportionately impacted by mandatory minimum sentences. Studies suggest Caucasians and African Americans use drugs at a similar rate: 8.8% and 9.6%, respectively (National Center for Health Statistics, 2012). However, African Americans are 13 times as more likely to be incarcerated for drug charges than Caucasians and constitute 62% of those incarcerated under mandatory minimum sentencing (Dumont, Brockmann, Dickman, Alexander, & Rich, 2012). Furthermore, African American and Latino offenders tend to serve longer terms than their Caucasian counterparts. For example, for those convicted of a powder cocaine that carries a mandatory minimum penalty, African American individuals serve approximately 110 months, Hispanic individuals serve 90 months, and Caucasian individuals serve about 70 months (National Center for Health Statistics, 2012). Caucasian offenders were also the most likely to be eligible for some sentencing relief; African American and Latino offenders were among the least likely (National Center for Health Statistics, 2012).
When offenders are incarcerated for long periods of time, the financial stress of a reduced-income family can lead remaining family members to poverty (Pratt, 2009). If the individual sent to prison on a drug offense was a contributing member to the family unit’s finances, the remaining family will have to take up the financial loss of the convicted family member’s absence (Smith & Hattery, 2010). Family members can find themselves in further economic crisis as they may also have ongoing financial reparations for the convicted drug charges that the family is expected to provide (Lynch, 2012; Pratt, 2009). For those who opt to regularly communicate with their family member during his/
4

her incarceration, it can be costly to maintain regular visits or phone calls (Grinstead, Faigeles, Bancroft, & Zack, 2001). One study notes that families with a family provider in prison report a significant increase in material distress during that individual’s imprisonment (Schwartz-Soicher, Geller, & Garfinkel, 2011).
Communities, as well, that relied on the offender’s legitimate contributions to society, in the forms of social and financial support, can suffer when many community members are removed for lengthy prison sentences (Pratt, 2009). For example, in some communities largely comprised of African Americans, a third of men between ages 14 and 35 may have been incarcerated for drug charges (National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse, 1998). These are prime years for working and building families that are disrupted by prison sentences; their lack o f presence and contribution in these communities can be correlated to less small businesses and home ownership-leaving other businesses and companies to chose not to bring their business to towns where there are less perceived qualified employees (Smith & Flattery, 2010). The result is a reduction of resources for the community, decrease in the overall financial security, and a lower socio-economic status (Finzen, 2005; Smith & Hattery, 2010).
Lengthy sentences can have negative, long-term impacts on an offender’s social network. Natural support networks, such as family and friends, can suffer over the course of time, increasing difficulty with re-entry adjustment. Due to long prison sentences that are often far from home or in constantly changing detention centers, it can be difficult for prisoners to maintain relationships with their families (Dumont et al., 2012; Grinstead et al., 2001; Mbuba, 2012).
5

Research shows that those who have served a prison sentence have decreased chances in securing employment or other financial support (Holzer, 1996; Kling, 2007; Mbuba, 2012). In one study of four major U.S. cities and their surrounding suburban areas, Holzer found that only a third of employers stated they would be willing to hire someone with a criminal background; on top of that, 29%-34% of employers absolutely require criminal background screenings prior to employment (1996). The same study suggests that 31-32% of employers would not consider hiring an employee who did not report work in the previous year, and 51-52% would not consider hiring someone with short-term or part-time work experience from the previous year (Holzer, 1996). Even though employers are often unwilling to hire someone with a criminal record or gaps in their employment history, one condition of parole is finding a job within the first month; those who cannot obtain employment are at risk of being found in violation of parole and sent back to prison (Mbuba, 2012).
Many may lack the skills and resume and have ongoing difficulties finding employment due to the length of time they spent in prison and not in broader society (Dumont et al., 2012). Those most likely to receive employment often find they must accept a low-paying job and work multiple jobs in order to make enough money (Seal, Eldrige, Kacanek, Binson, & MacGowan, 2007). Such consistently low-paying positions could have long-term effects, lowering the overall potential earning power for those who have a felony record (Kling, 1999). Some estimates suggest that potential earnings for those incarcerated between 1 to 6 years could reduce earnings in the 5 to 8 years post­ incarceration by 23%-31% (Kling; Western, Kling, & Weiman, 2001). Granted, this

number takes into consideration those from all income brackets upon imprisonment; the author of the study suggests that those in prison for violent crimes and drug offenses appeared to make lower money both when entering and leaving the criminal justice system (Kling, 1999).
Not everyone is able to work, and restrictions on public assistance can leave those released from prison financially restricted. For those who cannot work due to disabilities, they are unable to apply for benefits until release from prison; waiting for disability benefits to begin may take anywhere from 6 months to 2 years (Cloyes, Wong, Latimer, & Abarca, 2010). Some public benefits such as Temporary Assistance for Needy Families (TANF), as instituted in the Personal Responsibility and Work Opportunity Reconciliation Act, have stipulations that refuse aid to applicants who have a drug charge on their record (1996).
Such loss of income and support networks can increase vulnerabilities in other areas of life. With lack of stable income, those on parole are also at high risk of homelessness; studies show that somewhere between 10% and 27% of parolees are homeless (Law, 2005). Lack of financial opportunities may lead people to return to selling drugs as it is a familiar skill and an income opportunity (Mbuba, 2012). This, in turn, increases risk of recidivism—potentially incurring a more severe punishment for secondary or tertiary offenses—and contributing to the national recidivism rate of 52% (Katel, 2007).
Purpose of the Study It is important to examine the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 because some groups
7

of individuals experience disproportionate, negative, and long-lasting affects due to drug sentences. People of color, people with mental illnesses, and people of lower socio­ economic statuses have suffered disproportionately as a result of the Anti-Drug Abuse Act. As social workers work closely with these individuals and communities, they are bound to interact with individuals who have been affected by this legislation. A comprehensive knowledge of the intent and impact of these policies will inform social work practice. This analysis will conduct a thorough review of the policy’s objectives in tandem with studies of policy outcomes. This analysis will explore the effects of mandatory minimums on people of color, people with mental illnesses, and people of lower socio-economic statuses, as well as the impact on the communities these individuals have left behind due to lengthly absences due to mandatory minimum sentences.
Multicultural Relevance Research has shown the impact of current drug policies on marginalized individuals and communities (National Center for Health Statistics, 2012; Beck et al., 1993). People of color, lower socio-economic statuses, mental health statuses, and women have all found themselves disproportionately impacted by mandatory minimums (Lynch, 2012; Pratt, 2009). It is important for social workers to recognize how mandatory minimums affect these populations and advocate for policies that do not cause more harm to specific communities based on ethnicity, income, abilities, or gender.
Social Work Relevance In accordance with the National Association of Social Workers’ (NASW; 1999)

Code of Ethics, there are several key ethical considerations that should guide social work practice. One such consideration is social justice (NASW, 1999). As we have seen that mandatory minimum sentences have had a disproportionally negative effect on marginalized individuals and communities, we can determine the potential need for an intervention on the grounds of social injustice—to reduce the unequal consequences that some individuals seem to be facing based on their ethnicity, gender, or socio-economic status.
Another principle is the dignity and worth o f the individual (NASW, 1999). By considering the potential social injustices inflicted against the individual, we are valuing that person’s worth by addressing the injustices in light of the individual’s worth.
By engaging in the discussion around mandatory minimums, social workers are engaging in their responsibility to broader society. They are exploring and making known the impaired social well-being of individuals who have been given a mandatory minimum sentence. It is therefore a social worker’s responsibility to take social and political action, advocating for those who have suffered or been oppressed by the policy. As social work is also political, workers should be encouraged to spend time investing in the sociopolitical interests of those who have gone to prison for drug violations (Day, Casey, Ward, Howells, & Vess, 2010). Such advocacy is done in hopes o f equal administration ofjustice and equal hopes for improved quality of life.
