CHAPTER 2 LITERATURE REVIEW This section will review the literature related to the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986. It will explore the history of substance control, spanning from common use to criminalization. To examine the impact of strict, punitive legislative policies, this section will examine a case study of Prohibition. This section will also explore the general public’s historic to modem perspectives and responses to substance use. Finally, it will review the presidential administrations and their impact on legislation related to substance use leading to mandatory minimum sentencing. History of Substance Control In American history up until the 20th century, many currently illegal drugs had been previously legal and could even be purchased as over-the-counter medication (Harris, 2012; Bonnie & Whitebread, 1974). For example, pharmacists sold cocaine as an “instantaneous cure” for toothaches (Lloyd Manufacturing Co., 1885). Bayer marketed and sold heroin as a cough suppressant to manage symptoms o f whooping cough and bronchitis (Bayer Pharmaceutical Products, 1901). Mrs. Winslow’s Soothing Syrup contained morphine and was marketed for pain relief due to children’s teething and diarrhea (Swartz, 2012). A 92 proof medicine made of opium and alcohol was sold with dosage instructions for children as young as five days old (Stickney and Poor Spice Co., 1906).
10

But at the turn of the 20th century, researchers began to observe the various negative physiological effects of drugs. Studies showed cocaine was toxic and potentially lethal, causing restlessness, apprehension, paranoia, hallucinations, delirium, convulsions, and even lung and heart failure (Brain, 1925; Mattison, 1891). Morphine was noted to cause nervousness, irritability, and slowing of the heart; continued use over time could cause dependence and addiction (Gruber & Robinson, 1929; Tatum, Seevers, & Collins, 1929). One researcher, William Halsted, who used morphine on himself extensively in order to study its anesthetic properties, reportedly became so addicted to the substance that he used up to three times daily throughout the rest of his life (Olch, 1975). The result of such research was a growing awareness of the potential hazardous effects of drugs (Busch & Schnoll, 1985).
Those with political authority spread messages that those with drug addictions were in some way depraved for their inability to control cravings for drugs and more prone to commit crimes (Pratt, 2009; Walker, 1981; Bonnie & Whitebread, 1974). Those with substance addictions were considered “not only [...] worthless to society,” but they were also “willing to commit any crime” to get drugs (Buell, 1925, p. 1). Drug addiction became considered “an evil habit [that] should be destroyed” (Anslinger & Tompkins, 1953, p. 295).
In response to growing research and public urging, policies were enacted to restrict the distribution and ready availability of substances that had a potentially harmful effect on people and society (Harris, 2012). The Harrison Narcotics Act of 1914 regulated the production, importation, and distribution of opiates in the United States.
11

Similarly, the Marihuana Tax of 1937 regulated marijuana by imposing a tax on marijuana sales and fines up to $2000 for those who did not abide by federal regulations.
Case Study of Federally-Mandated Substance Control: Prohibition Special interest groups in society gained momentum to lobby for policies that would make harmful substances less readily-accessible to the general public (Cherrington, 1920; Moore & Gerstein, 1981; Tyrrell, 1997). The Women’s Temperance Movement and the Anti-Saloon League organized and campaigned for the prohibition of alcohol (Cherringon, 1920). They accused alcohol o f impairing the security of the family unit, contributing towards domestic violence, leaving children to be raised without paternal guidance (Lender & Martin, 1982; Moore & Gerstein, 1981; Okrent, 2010). The public believed the long-term results would be an increase in alcoholism, national poverty, and crime (Moore & Gerstein, 1981). Prohibition supporters dispersed propaganda with scenes of children suffering domestic violence under the care of intoxicated parents to convey the potential severity of alcohol to the general public (Moore & Gerstein, 1981). In 1917, the 18th amendment was passed and the production and distribution of alcohol was made illegal in the United States (U.S. Const, amend. XVIII, repealed 1933). Enforcement for the 18th amendment was outlined in 1919 by the Volstead Act (repealed 1933): any person found guilty o f manufacturing or distributing alcohol was subject to a fine up to $1000 and a sentence up to 6 months; second offenses were subject to a fine between $200 and $2,000 and a prison sentence between 1 month and 5 years.
12

It is difficult to know exactly how many people consumed alcohol during this time, due to ever-changing research criteria and a general hesitancy to admit to engaging in illegal consumption of alcohol (Crossen, 2005; Lender & Martin, 1982). However, there was significant evidence to support the sustained prevalence of alcohol (Crossen. 2005; Murdock, 1998). Grape production in Napa Valley increased significantly during prohibition; vineyards produced 56 million gallons in 1921, while 137 gallons were produced in 1924 (Crossen, 2005). In spite of the law, speakeasies, nightclubs, and cabarets, places to engage in alcoholic consumption, grew in popularity (Crossen, 2005; Murdock, 1998). In New York, there were 5,000 speakeasies in New York; 5 years later, there were 30,000 (Crossen, 2005). This suggests that although breweries, distilleries and wineries could no longer legally operate due to the law (U.S. Const, amend. XVm, repealed 1933; Volstead Act, 1919, repealed 1933), the market for alcoholic beverages persisted during prohibition (Crossen, 2005; Murdock, 1998).
Public demand for alcohol created opportunities for oiganized crime rings to profit by providing the supply illegally (Beshears, 2010). Gangsters like Al Capone were suspected of running multi-million dollar industries that profited from bootlegging of alcohol (Lender & Martin, 1982). Instead o f reducing crime through the prohibition of alcohol, crime actually gained momentum during prohibition (Beshears, 2010; Asbridge & Weerasinghe, 2009; Yablonsky, 1997). During the 1920s, the first drive-by shootings occurred and became common amongst American gangsters (Yablonsky, 1997). A study examining the effect of prohibition on violent crime in Chicago showed that the total number of homicides in the city increased by 22% (Asbridge & Weerasinghe, 2009).
13

Prohibition lost public support during the Great Depression. Women, a previously critical group supporting Prohibition, became concerned with other issues outside of the household during the period of suffrage (Lender & Martin, 1982). Arguments written by opponents insisted Prohibition demoralized the public and bred oiganized crime (Cherrington, 1926). After the stock market crash, repeal seemed advantageous as legitimizing the alcohol industry would create employment opportunities and generate significant funds for the economy (Lender & Martin, 1982). In 1933, the 18th amendment was overturned by the 21st amendment and alcohol was again legalized and regulated (U.S. Const, amend. XXI).
Public Opinion and Previous Legislation since 1950 Types of Policies
In reviewing drug control policies since the 1950s, one can see drug policies tend to alternate from punitive, supply-reduction policies to rehabilitative, demand-reduction policies (Eddy, 2003; Hawdon, 2001). Supply-reduction policies tend to focus on ways to end the supply of drugs, primarily by incarcerating those who were caught selling or in possession of drugs (Eddy). These policies tend to be more punitive in nature as they concentrated on the punishment of those caught in violation of drug laws (Bonnie & Whitebread, 1974; Hawdon, 2001). Alternately, demand-reduction policies sought to reduce the public’s demand of illicit substances (Eddy, 2003). These policies were therapeutic in nature and included opportunities for rehabilitation from drug addiction as opposed to immediate incarceration (Hawdon, 2001).
14

195Q& By the 1950s, rising drug and crime rates were at the forefront of die public
attention (Bonnie & Whitebread, 1974; M.M. Gill, 2008). While in 1948 newspapers reported total arrests for narcotic and marijuana violations were at 3,895, the next year, the total number had risen to 5,273—a 135% increase (Bureau of Narcotics and United States Customs Services as cited in “Narcotics Arrests Show Sharp Rise”, 1950). Other statistics suggested a more conservative, though still significant, growth of drug-related crime and activity, such as a 70% increase in narcotic violations between 1948 and 1950 (Congressional Record, 1951). Drugs and drug-related crime became a lengthy conversation at congressional hearings (Kefauver Committee Hearings, 1951). Congressman Boggs, who championed harsh penalties for drug violations, presented information on increasing drug addiction from eleven magazine articles between May and July of 1951 to a congressional meeting (Congressional Record, 1951).
As a consequence of these hearings, two policies were passed to address the apparent drug problem (Bonnie & Whitebread, 1974). The Boggs Act of 1951 (repealed 1970) imposed the first mandatory minimum sentences for possession and trafficking of illegal drugs. First time offenders received a 2-year minimum sentence; second time offenders faced a 5-year minimum sentence. Anyone charged with a narcotic offense was denied opportunity for parole after the first offense (Boggs Act of 1951, repealed 1970). Five years later, Congress enacted the Narcotics Control Act of 1956 (repealed 1970), which expanded upon the Boggs Act by increasing mandatory sentence minimums by 5 years for first-time offenses and 10 years for second-time offenses. These policies were
15

structured in a way to reduce the supply of drugs by incarcerating drug offenders (Bonnie & Whitehead, 1974). Many were incarcerated for drug-related crimes after the implementation of these laws, and both criminal justice representatives and families of those in prison pressured Congress to amend the legislation (Campbell, 2009; Mascharka, 2000).
mos
In spite of these laws, reports confirmed drug use had not only failed to decrease after the policy’s implementation, but appeared to increase during the 1960s as well (Beckett, 1994; Campbell, 2009; S. Rep. No. 91-613,1969; Mascharka, 2000; Pratt, 2007. As there are scant scientific studies to verify this claim, it is unclear whether substance use did indeed increase at this time; perhaps it was simply the public’s awareness of substance use that grew as drugs like marijuana became closely associated with the political movements of the 1960s (Bonnie & Whitebread, 1974). Still, Gallup reports showed most Americans were fearful for the potential harmful effects of drugs like marijuana: 60% believed the drug was physically addictive; some were even under the impression that it could cause anything from acne to blindness (Robison, 2002). In a 1969 poll, 48% of respondents believed drug use was a serious issue in their neighborhoods (Robison, 2002). Available information suggests the only drug to exceed the demand of marijuana was cocaine (Walker, 1981).
When he came into his presidency in 1963, Lyndon Johnson led efforts to increase federal capacity to address drug-related issues. In a public address, he asserted that drug use was inflicting “enormous damage in human suffering [and] crime” and the federal
16

government bore responsibility to regulate and punish such activity (Johnson, par. 1, 1964). In 1968, the Bureau of Narcotics and Dangerous Drugs (BNDD) was created to extend the power of the federal government to exert both local and international control related to drugs. The BNDD established task forces that explored ways to reduce the availability of drugs in America; their discussions were partially responsible for increases in national drug sentences (Lynch, 2012). Legislation passed during the Johnson administration was more therapeutic in nature; for example, the 1966 Narcotics Addict Rehabilitation Act allowed those addicted to methamphetamine to seek treatment as an alternate to punitive prison sentences (Yuill, 2009). 1970s
By the 1970s, drug use seemed to be still on the rise; while in 1969, only 4% of American adults reported having tried marijuana, that rate had tripled by 1973 and doubled again by 1977 (Robison, 2002). A representative sample study suggested that, in the past 6 months, 16.8% of young adults age 18-24 had used marijuana and 3% had used stimulants (Gove, Geerken, & Hughes, 1979). In 1967, it is estimated there were 1.3 million new marijuana users; 5 years later, it was estimated there were 3.5 million new users that year (Gfroerer & Brodsky, 1992). In 1972, an estimated 469,000 new people tried cocaine; in 1979, 1.4 million people are believed to have tried cocaine for the first time (Gfroerer & Brodsky, 1992).
Media coverage appeared to have been manipulated for the sake of creating an even more drastic response from the general public (Orcutt & Turner, 1993; Reeves & Campbell, 1994). For example, a Newsweek story conveyed an infographic about the
17

stark and dramatic increase in substance use which, when looking at the raw data, had only increased marginally (Orcutt & Turner, 1993). In a 1971 report, figures showed an drastic increase in those with heroin addictions from 68,000 in 1969 to 559,000 that year; however, this increase was easily attributed to a change in data interpretation policies when the BNDD began to estimate for potentially missing data by quadrupling the actual data (Epstein, 1977).
In 1971, President Nixon was the first to publicly declare a “war on drugs” (Yuill, 2009, p. 144) and that “America’s public enemy number one is drug abuse” (Yuill, 2009, p. 147). These messages demonstrate a political rhetoric when responding to the problems associated with drug use that impacted the general public (Beckett, 1994; Yuill, 2009). These messages were conveyed to a large public audience and played a significant role in defining and gaining support for anti-drug legislation (Yuill). For example, President Nixon once stated each heroin addict could create six more addicts, further confounding the public’s fear on drug use (Epsten, 1977).
Yet under President Nixon, drug policies began to transition from punitive and law-enforcement driven, to more liberal, demand-reduction policies (Cooper, 2000; Lynch, 2012). Previous policies, like the Boggs Act and the Narcotic Control Act, were considered failures as mandatory minimums had not proven to reduce drug use in America (Mascharka, 2000). These laws were repealed by the Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act of 1970. This law was more liberal as it revoked the punitive mandatory minimum sentences and reduced maximum sentences (Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act, 1970; Cooper, 2000). Also
18

within the law, a scheduling table was created which assigns degrees o f punitive sanctions based upon weight of and type of confiscated substances, a practice which would be mirrored in future legislation (Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act, 1970). The highly addictive nature of cocaine was also acknowledged within the policy by its classification as a schedule 2 drug (Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act, 1970).
More closely reflecting previous supply-reduction policies, the Drug Enforcement Agency (DEA) replaced the BNDD and was tasked to fight and punish organized crime related to heroin, cocaine, PCP, and marijuana (Lynch, 2012). But additional policies focused on demand-reduction. For example, President Nixon created the National Clearinghouse of Drug Abuse Information and Education as a central point of contact for the general public (Nixon, 1970). To fund their work, President Nixon asked for and received $105 million from Congress to use for drug treatment and rehabilitation (Nixon, 1970; Yuill, 2009). 1980s
The media had previously been a powerful medium to propagate the message of the potential dangers of drugs (Bonnie & Whitebread, 1974; Moore & Gerstein, 1981), but by the 1980s, the media became even more influential, using dramatic images to inform public awareness and opinion regarding over increased drug prevalence (Beckett, 1994; Orcutt & Turner, 1993). An analysis of public opinion surveys from the mid 1960s through the 1980s showed that public concern over drug-related crime was closely related to media coverage of crime and drugs (Beckett, 1994). In fact, public concern over drug-
19

related crime more closely matched media coverage than the actual growth o f drugrelated crime rates (Beckett, 1994). For example, although media coverage of illicit drug use was frequent during the early 1980s (Reeves & Campbell, 1994), past 30 day illicit drug use amongst those 12 and over had actually decreased from 13.7% in 1979 to 12.2% in 1982 (Tlmrots & Byrne, 1995). The media’s messages of the dangers of drugs were also constant; in a review of major newspapers publications over a forty-week period, there were 406 stories about cocaine (Reeves & Campbell, 1994).
The result was a growing societal concern about the rising prevalence of cocaine and other substance use (Beckett, 1994). By 1988, nearly 39% of the general population believed drug-related crime activity was the most important problem the nation faced; in 1971, only 5.5% of the population would have agreed (Gallup, 1991). In response to the perceived dangers of rising drug use, the general public demonstrated a type of “moral panic” (Hawdon, 2001, p. 420) and supported drug policies that have been perceived as morally driven and excessively punitive (King, 1971; Lynch, 2012).
As with Nixon, President Reagan often discussed how drugs were “harming our people” and staked “as much a threat to the United States as enemy planes and missiles,” employing the familiar wartime rhetoric in his discussion of drugs in America (Reagan as cited in Hawdon, 2001). His speeches often emphasized that participation in drug-related activities was a personal choice, furtherjustifying the application of punitive sanctions to those who chose to engage in drug-related activities (Hawdon, 2001). Even Mrs. Reagan took a public stance against drugs, coining the familiar “just say no” message to teach children to make the personal choice to refrain from drug use (Reagan, 1986a). As the
20

media effectively tied drugs and crime together in the public opinion (Pratt, 2009; Reeves & Campbell, 1994), and the president espoused how personal choices were responsible for rising drug prevalence, policy-makers changed their strategy in drug policy. Reagan’s administration strayed from demand-reduction perspective back towards previous supplyreduction strategies and strict punitive measures to address rising crime and drug rates (Cooper, 2000; Eddy, 2003; Timrots & Byrne, 1995).
For example, the Comprehensive Crime Control Act of 1984 set the scene for harsher penalties on drug-related offenses. It lay the groundwork to distinguish between higher-level offenders and lesser-level offenders, determined by prior history of drug possession or connection to organized crime (Comprehensive Crime Control Act, 1984). Orders for criminal forfeiture of assets related to drug-related charges previously outlined by the Organized Crime Control Act of 1970 were expanded by the Comprehensive Crime Control Act as new funds were created to collect higher amounts of asset seizures (1984).
This act also created the United States Sentencing Commission (Comprehensive Crime Control Act, 1984). The goal of this commission was to create uniformity and reduce disparities in sentence outcomes (Comprehensive Crime Control Act, 1984; Lynch, 2012). The outcome was a series of mandatory minimum sentences for charges ranging from violent crimes to drug related crime (Comprehensive Crime Control Act, 1984; Lynch). These guidelines would have a profound effect on the corrections system over the next few years. Within 7 years, the average length of time served nearly tripled, raising from under 30 months to 80 months (United States Sentencing Commission,
21

2004). Yet the public’s concern over drug use had not waned. In a follow-up attempt to
reduce drug use and drug-related crime, the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 was intended to strategically target drug dealers. The amount of drugs confiscated by law enforcement was intended to serve as a guide to identify the high-level dealers from lower-level offenders (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). Distinctions were also made between which types of drugs deserved harsher penalties. For example, harsher penalties were instituted for those in possession of crack cocaine rather than powder cocaine (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). For the past 26 years, mandatory minimums have become commonplace in our society, deeply impacting and shaping our prisons and communities.
Summary In the past century, America has seen a profound change in the way it responds to drug use. While it was at one point regulated and monitored, emerging information on the dangers of substances caused authorities to restrict the wide-spread use of drugs like cocaine, heroin, and marijuana. Americans have seen several failed attempts in the regulation process: ranging from the Prohibition of alcohol in the 1920s to the initial mandatory minimums imposed on those in possession of drugs during the 1950s and 1960s. As media and politicians continued to propagate the message of the dangers of drugs, the general population’s desire to stifle any possession or distribution o f drugs also increased. Throughout the 1960s and to the 1980s, Americans became increasingly concerned with the drug “epidemic” and supported policies that would restrict their prevalence. At the height o f the concern, the Anti Drug-Abuse Act o f 1986 was created.
22

However, as this policy has appeared to fail to address Americans’ concerns with drugs and crime, it is high time for the policy to be reviewed and adapted to better meet the needs of all Americans.
