CHAPTER 4 POLICY ANALYSIS The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 was signed into law on October 27,1986. This policy has many provisions in regards to defining, enforcing, and punishing various drug crimes. This analysis, however, focuses on the mandatory minimums sentences under Title I, Subtitle A, known as the Narcotics Penalties and Enforcement Act. This section outlined punishments for those found in possession o f illicit substances. Punishments were contingent upon three variables: (1) the substance itself, (2) the amount of the substance found in the violator’s possession, and (3) the violator’s previous record. Different punishments were outlined and implemented to distinguish between lower-level offenders (in possession o f less amounts of illicit substance) and higher-level offenders (in possession of more amounts of illicit substances). For example, someone in possession of 500 grams of powder cocaine would be subject to a mandatory minimum sentence of 5 years for a first time offense; however, if that same person was in possession of 5 kilograms of cocaine, he or she would be subject to a 10year minimum sentence. If the violation was not a first-time offense, the minimum punishments would respectively change to 10 and 20 years (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). Section A: Issues Dealt with by the Policy The Anti-Drug Abuse Act o f 1986 was created to address the rising prevalence of drugs in America. Drugs were viewed as physically dangerous to those who used them
27

(Busch & Schnoll, 1985; Robison, 2002). Crack cocaine, which received the harshest penalties according to the previsions in this act, was believed to be more dangerous and physically addictive than other drugs; it was also believed to be used by more dangerous and violent drug users (Kimbrough v. United States, 2002). President Reagan considered it “an explosively destructive and often lethal substance which is crushing its users” (1986a, par. 6). Youth were thought to be in danger of the ill effects of drugs as the rising drug prevalence affected school-aged children as well; in 1980,37.2% of high school seniors reported using an illegal substance in the previous month (Timrots & Byrne, 1995). Participation in drug activity was believed to break down the security of the family unit by distracting from one’s familial role in order to feed one’s habit (Bonnie and Whitebread, 1974; Pratt, 2009; Walker, 1981). However, it is interesting to note that the substance most guilty of incurring abuse and family violence is alcohol—a substance that is not addressed in this policy (National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse, 1998). Illicit substance use was feared to impair an adult’s ability to contribute to his or her community through gainful employment (Buell, 1925; Pratt, 2009; Reagan, 1986a). New policies that addressed drugs were therefore viewed as protecting American youth, adults, families, and the safety of the nation (Hawdon, 2001).
Furthermore, the policy was designed to reduce drug-related crime in America (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). In 1982,12.2% ofAmericans age 12 and over had used illicit substances in the past month (Timrots & Byrne, 1995). Throughout the 1980s, it was estimated 29% of those in federal prison for a violent crime were regular drug users (National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse, 1998). Of those in federal prison in
28

1980, 33% o f those who commit a violent crime were under the influence o f mindaltering substances, including alcohol; excluding alcohol, 16% of those in federal prison were under the influence o f illegal drugs at the time of committing a violent offense (National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse, 1998).
Policy-makers believed that drug use was inextricably related to crime because drug users would commit any variety o f crimes in order to obtain the drugs needed to sustain their habit (Bonnie & Whitebread, 1974; Buell, 1925; Pratt, 2009; Walker, 1981). Actual reports suggest that 10% of those in federal prison and 17% of those in state prison commit crimes in order to obtain drugs (National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse, 1998). Still, policy-makers believed that reducing the supply and demand of drugs would thereby reduce the crime rate (Eddy, 2003). Mandatory minimum sentences were employed to reduce the supply of drugs, thereby reducing drugrelated crime and violent crime.
Section B: Objectives. Value Premises. Theoretical Positions. Target Segments, and Substantive Effects of the Policy
Policy Objectives The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 was comprised of fifteen titles that each
address a different aspect of drug control and enforcement. Title One, the Narcotics Penalties and Enforcements Act, was designed to amend the Controlled Substances Act o f 1970 by requiring mandatory minimum sentences for those caught in possession of illegal substances (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). The policy’s overt objective included employing lengthy, uniform sentences—from 5 years to life—to those who violated drug laws (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). The policy granted the Federal government increased
29

power to decide and employ punishments for drug offenders. Mandated sentences eliminated judge discretion and variance when sentencing; sentences became uniformly applied as outlined in the policy (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986).
First time offenders could receive a five year mandatory minimum sentence if they had 100 grams of heroin, 500 grams of cocaine powder, 5 grams of cocaine base, 100 grams of PCP, 1 gram of LSD, 40 grams of methamphetamine, or 100 kilograms of marijuana. After the first offense, the same amounts of illicit substance incurred a ten year mandatory minimum sentence. A second sentencing schedule outlined the even more severe punishments for those caught in possession of ten times the previous amounts listed. First time offenders would receive a mandatory ten year sentence when they had 1 kilogram of heroin, 5 kilograms of powder cocaine, 50 grams of cocaine base, 1 kilogram of PCP, 10 grams of LSD, 400 grams of methamphetamine, or 1000 kilograms of marijuana. Second time offenses with the same amount would incur a 20 year minimum sentence (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986).
The covert objectives of this policy were to remove drug users from general society for long periods of time. Prior to this policy’s implementation, drug users could cycle in and out of the criminal justice system, returning to the community more quickly than after the policy’s implementation. In 1982, the average sentence for all drug violations was 55 months (National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse, 1998). However, after this policy’s implementation, drug users could spend anywhere from 5 years to a life sentence in prison for their drug charges (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). By 1994, those charged with drug violations were serving an average sentence of 80 months
30

for the same crimes (National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse). This policy keeps drug users removed and isolated from society. Some political advisors suggest this was done in order to protect the nation’s safety from die harmful effects o f drug use and related crime (Eddy, 2003).
One could argue this policy also had a covert objective to impact the African American community at a disproportionate rate to the Caucasian community (Alexander, 2010; Vagins & McCurdy, 2006). Crack cocaine, which was available in small quantities, cost anywhere between $3 and $35 and was more easily available in low-income and African American communities (United States Department o f Justice, 2002). Its powder counterpart, which generally cost $100 a gram, was more easily used by higher income and Caucasian communities (United States Department o f Justice). Crack cocaine incurred a mandatory minimum sentence that was disproportionately severe compared to the mandatory minimum sentence for powder cocaine or any other substance listed in the policy (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). This has become well known as the 100:1 ratio, disproportionately affecting those who use crack cocaine over powder (Lynch, 2012; United States Department o f Justice; Vagins & McCurdy, 2006). Those caught in possession o f five grams o f crack cocaine are subject to 5 years for the first offense; those caught with five hundred grams of powder cocaine are subject to the same punishment (Pub. L. 99-570). Interesting to note, however, that these two substances have no inherent differences; they are the same substance, in different stages of the preparation, that cause the same affects in the user (Vagins & McCurdy, 2006).
31

Values This policy espouses the value that America should be free from drug activity.
The reasoning behind the implementation of the Anti-Drug Abuse Act reflects a dedication to the eradication of drugs in the nation (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). Reasoning becomes moral in nature as it follows the belief that one should not use drugs. This is likely due to the widespread belief that drug use inherently hinders one’s ability to be a functioning member o f society, creates non-productivity amongst users, and contradicts the American work ethic (Bonnie & Whitebread, 1974; Pratt, 2009; Walker, 1981). In particular, Americans were highly concerned about drug prevalence among youth in the 1980s (Kefauver Committee Hearings, 1951; Orcutt & Turner, 1993). Enacting harsh laws was a way for policy-makers to address and hopefully reduce the seemingly epidemic drug use among American youth (Dorsey & Middleton, 2008; Kefauver Committee Hearings, 1951). President Reagan saw youth drug use as “especially damaging” as young people are the ones “on whom [the nation’s] future depends” (Reagan, 1986b, par. 2). This motivation to protect youth reflects a value that it is the duty o f society to protect American youth and America’s future from the dangers o f drugs (Reagan, 1986b). Theoretical Positions
This policy reflects the understanding that engagement in drug possession, use, and criminal activity in general are personal choices. Therefore, if an individual breaks the law, it would be fitting to punish that individual for his or her personal decisions and actions (Priestley & Vanstone, 2010). If the individual was left to his or her own
32

deviancy, his or her actions could victimize innocent people or influence others to conduct themselves in a similar deviant manner (Priestley & Vanstone, 2010). In this case, “everyone's safety [was] at stake” as drug users could have the potential to victimize the public through drug related crime or influence others to further engage in drug use (Reagan, 1986a, par. 7). In a public address, President Reagan implored the significance o f enacting anti-drug laws by informing the public that “drugs are menacing our society. They're threatening our values and undercutting our institutions. They're killing our children” (Reagan, 1986a, par. 3). Therefore, those who engaged in drug activity were potentially dangerous as their actions had the potential to fragment or corrupt society (Reagan, 1986a). Punishment, then, is a tool to keep such deviant behavior suppressed and preserve the safety and culture of the nation (Priestley & Vanstone, 2010; Reagan, 1986a).
There are different philosophies as to how to enact punishment within policy. The mandatory minimum sentences employed by the Anti-Drug Abuse Act o f 1986 relied upon a punitive philosophy o f punishment. The policy was created under the supplyreduction hypothesis that argued severe drug policies would reduce motivation for drug users to sell for fear o f harsh punishment (Hawdon, 2001; Rapadas, 2004). This, in turn, would reduce the motivation o f drug dealers to sell for fear of long incarceration terms if caught (Lynch, 2012). Eventually this reduced desire to deal drugs would reduce the supply of drugs in America by the incarceration, and therefore isolation, of high level drug users (Lynch, 2012; Rapadas, 2004; Vincent & Hofer, 1994). The long-range effect would be a reduction in the crime-rate through the incarceration and removal from
33

society of those individuals who were drug offenders (Blomberg, 2000). The desire to eradicate drug use in America reflected the President’s “commitment not to tolerate drugs by anyone, anytime, anyplace” (Reagan, 1986a, par. 30).
The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 enacted a shift in the philosophy behind drug policies. Previous policies focused on reducing the demand for illicit substances by treating those who were prone to engage in illicit drug activity (Hawdon, 2001). With this policy, previous allowances for therapy and parole were removed (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). The focus shifted to the potential efficacy o f lengthy sentences to reduce the high drug prevalence from greater society (Eddy, 2003; Reagan, 1986a). Target Population
This policy was directed towards adults of all races who used and/or distributed drugs in America (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). More specifically, it was intended to disrupt users with a large supply of substances who were likely dealing as well. The policy does not explicitly say it is intended to be applied to one group over another. However, it is interesting to note that the penalties for the substances provide some insight to underlying target segments. For example, the structure of the policy distinguishes crack cocaine from powder cocaine, implementing different punishments for each offense. During this time, crack cocaine was seen as more common amongst communities of color, particularly amongst African American men (Alexander, 2010). It could be suggested that the disparity in punishments for cocaine use detailed in this policy was intended to affect African Americans more severely, as they were more wellknown to use crack cocaine (Alexander, 2010).
34

Short and Long Term Intended Effects of the Policy A review of the literature suggests that the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 failed to
achieve its intended effects. Research that has emerged since the policy’s implementation has not supported the efficacy of mandatory minimums on reducing the availability of drugs in America (United States Sentencing Commission, 2010; Vincent & Hofer, 1994). Only 10% of those incarcerated under mandatory minimums were considered high-level suppliers or dealers; 62.4% of those incarcerated were low-level offenders in 2009 (United States Sentencing Commission, 2010).
Within the first decade o f the policy’s enactment, high school seniors report they can obtain illegal drugs at similar rates as they were prior to the policy’s implementation. In fact, the ease of obtaining LSD and heroin increased slightly from 32% and 21% in 1982 to 44% and 35% in 1992, respectively (Vincent & Hofer, 1994). More recently in a 2010 Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration (SAMHSA) survey o f youth age 12-17 on the perceived ease to obtain drugs, 51% believed they could obtain marijuana, 24.9% could obtain powder cocaine, 25.3% could obtain crack cocaine, 14% could obtain heroin, and 15.7% could obtain LSD (2011).
The national drug rate has remained relatively consistent amongst adults for the past decade. In 2002, the national drug prevalence for adults over 26 was about 5.8%; in 2010, the rate had increased slightly to 6.6% (SAMHSA, 2011). The age group that has most regularly used illicit drugs has been 18-25 year olds (SAMHSA, 2011). In 2002, 20.2% had used illegal drugs in the previous month; this number continued to decrease slightly to 19.6% in 2008. The number again increased to 21.5% in 2010 (SAMHSA,
35

2011). Since 2002, only 1% of the population age 12 and older have been monthly cocaine users (SAMHSA, 2012).
Research over the past 20 years has also suggested that mandatory minimum sentences have had no significant effect on the second desired effect: reducing the incidence o f drug-related violent crime (Dorsey & Middleton, 2008; Vincent & Hofer, 1994). In 1987, drug-related homicides were at 4.9% (Dorsey & Middleton, 2008). Ironically, it was after the policy’s implementation, drug-related homicides actually increased, peaking in 1989 at 7.4% (Dorsey & Middleton, 2008).
Since then, drug-related homicides continued to decrease; by 2007,3.9% of homicides were related to drugs (Dorsey & Middleton, 2008). The decrease in drugrelated homicides did not coincide with policy implementation, but is more likely tied to the fact that American economy improved in the 1990s, a sign that often correlates with a general decrease in drugs and crime (Pratt, 2009). In general, weapon use only occurred in a small fiaction of offenses; only 2.3% of crack cocaine users had a weapon in their possession at the time of the offense (United States Sentencing Guidelines, 2007). Unintended Effects of die Policy
Perhaps Chief Justice William Rehnquist said it best when he claimed this policy was riddled with “unintended consequences” (2005, par. 20). Not only have the intended effects of reducing drug use and drug-related violent crime in America not been achieved, there have also been several significant unintentional effects. The unintended effects directly affected the target population by keeping prisoners incarcerated for so long, that the prisons have begun overcrowding at alarming rates (United States Sentencing
36

Commission, 2011). Unintended effects also include impacts to the non-target population by impacting unrelated policy development (Alexander, 2010; Harlow, 2001; Walsh, 2007). Perhaps most notably, this policy has created stark inequalities for women and African Americans who enter prison for drug charges (Alexander, 2010; Lenora, Luthra, Verma, Small, Allard, & Levingston, 2005; Mauer & King, 2007; Vagins & McCurdy, 2006).
Prison population growth. Because o f this policy, the prison population has swelled. By 1989, the average time served in prison for possession charges increased 159% (Simon, 1993). Up to 70% of this growth was attributed to mandatory minimum sentencing (Vincent & Hoffer, 1994). By 1991, the average term increased again to 72 months (Clark, 1994). By 2010, the average sentence was 132 months (United States Sentencing Commission, 2011). With people spending longer time in prison, the prison population has dramatically increased. There are currently over 2 million people presently incarcerated (Katel, 2007).
Impacts on future policies. Another unintended effect of employing mandatory minimum sentences was the impact of the nature of this policy on future policy development. After the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986, additional punitive policies directed towards drug users have been employed. Three-strikes laws, which twentyseven states have enacted, are also forms of fixed sentencing guidelines that have long­ term results for those convicted (Walsh, 2007). Non-correctional policies continue to punish drug users once they have served their prison sentence. Benefit programs like Temporary Assistance for Needy Families (TANF) have stipulations that refuse aid to
37

applicants who have a drug charge on their record (Personal Responsibility and Work Opportunity Reconciliation Act, 1996). Twelve states have laws that prohibit those with felonies to vote in elections, further marginalizing their political power to advocate for themselves and their communities’ needs (Alexander, 2010; Dumont et al., 2012). Alternately, other charges received more sentence leniency in order to reduce the number o f people in prison for extended periods o f time. For example, a person who is convicted of a violent offense without a firearm may serve an average sentence of 87 months— someone who commits assault may expect to spend the same amount o f time in prison as someone with a drug possession charge (Harlow, 2001).
Currently, the Obama administration is taking strides towards alleviating some of the sentencing disparities with the policy. His is the first presidential administration since Nixon to stop using the term “war on drugs.” In a 2012 report to Congress, President Obama and his staff outlined a need to better address drug abuse in preventative, early healthcare efforts and better integrate treatment options into drug law reform (United States Executive Office, 2012). He also signed into law the Fair Sentencing Act, which sought to retroactively reduce the 100:1 disparity in crack to powder cocaine sentencing (2010). Rather than using the threshold of five and 500 grams, this policy changes the threshold to 28 and 280 grams (Fair Sentencing Act, 2010). However, this policy fails to truly equalize sentencing practices, as the threshold amounts to incur mandatory minimums for powder cocaine is 500 grams and 5 kilograms (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986).
Populations Affected. Over time, this policy has dramatically affected various 38

groups. Women, for example, have been negatively affected by mandatory minimums. Between 1986 and 2005, there has been an 888% increase in women incarcerated for drug crimes—particularly because of mandatory minimums; this increase far surpasses the rate at which men are incarcerated (Lenora, Luthra, Verma, Small, Allard, & Levingston, 2005). Also, 58% o f women in federal prison have been incarcerated for drug charges (Lenora et al., 2005). Women who are incarcerated face additional family and parenting hardships, particularly if they are single parents (Vagins & McCurdy, 2006). Children are three times more likely to live with a parent if their father, rather than their mother, goes to prison; if children do not live with a parent, the impact on the children could range from temporary foster care to permanent displacement (Lenora et al., 2005).
In particular, African American men and communities of color have been the most dramatically affected by this law. African Americans are 13 times as more likely to be incarcerated for drug charges than Caucasians and constitute 62% of those incarcerated under mandatory minimum sentencing (Dumont, Brockmann, Dickman, Alexander, & Rich, 2012). Although 66% of crack cocaine users are white or Hispanic, over 80% of those sentenced for crack violations are African Americans (Vagins & McCurdy, 2006). Before mandatory minimum sentences were enacted, African Americans served federal sentences that were on average 11% higher than Caucasians; by 1990, African Americans served a federal sentence that was 49% higher (Vagins & McCurdy, 2006). For powder cocaine, African Americans face an average sentence o f 153 months compared to Caucasians who receive an average of 131 months (United States Sentencing Commission, 2011). Largely due to the terms of the policy, African Americans serve
39

terms for drug crimes nearly as long as Caucasian offenders serve for violent crimes, 58.7 months and 61.7 months respectively (Mauer & King, 2007). Within a decade of the policy’s implementation, one in every 29 African American men was in prison for a drug charge (National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse, 1998). The structure and impact of this legislation have been equated to a modem Jim Crow for the effect it has had on systematically oppressing African Americans, segregating them from the community at large, and inhibiting their chances to succeed (Alexander, 2010).
Incarceration can hinder African American opportunities to get ahead in life through higher education. By 1996, only a decade after the policy’s implementation, there were 500,000 African American men in prison, compared to 100,000 in higher education (National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse, 1998). In 2000, there were more African American men in prison and jail than in higher education (Justice Policy Institute, 2002). If African Americans are incarcerated during prime years to enroll in higher education, they may miss improved employment opportunities that could have been obtained by a post-secondary degree. Furthermore, the government itself is spending more money to lock up African Americans than to put them through higher education. It’s estimated that, since this policy’s implementation, the government annually spends about $2.8 billion on higher education for African Americans and $10 on incarceration (Justice Policy Institute, 2002).
When more African American men go to prison, there are less left at home to serve as positive role models to their communities. While incarcerated, they are unable to marry others and begin families. They cannot serve as examples to their children at
40

home and many youth may be raised without fathers. Incarceration disallows African American men to provide for their families and communities through financial contributions from gainful employment and taxes. This could potentially plunge a community into economic despair when droves of individuals within a community are imprisoned for lengthly periods of time (Pratt, 2009). Social and economic factors such as these can actually contribute to and increase the likelihood that more individuals living under these circumstances will use drugs, thus continuing the cycle o f drug prevalence in these communities (Fothergill, Ensminger, Green, Robertson, & Juon, 2009; Thompson & Uggen, 2012).
Yet consequences of this policy affect more than the individual who was convicted. The families of those who were convicted have long-lasting financial and social repercussions as well. Families expend exorbitant amounts o f money to see their families, travel if their family members are relocated to a nonlocal prison, and even pay reparations for the incarcerated’s crime (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 2986; Lynch, 2012; Pratt, 2009; Schwartz-Soicher, Geller, & Garfinkel, 2011). This money spent to either provide support or maintain a relationship with an incarcerated friend or family member could detract from contributions to the general public’s welfare; missed time work and school absences can hinder the family’s economic and educational well-being (SchwartzSoicher, Geller, & Garfinkel, 2011). Furthermore, this money could be paid into the person’s community through taxes, but is rather given to the criminal justice system for everything from trial to prison costs. For communities that have a high amount of incarcerated family members, such expenditures could compound already existent
41

community financial depression due to low socioeconomic statuses (Pratt, 2009). Mandatory minimums have unintentional, long-lasting affects on an individual’s
quality o f life. Those incarcerated will likely be sent to an overcrowded prison where they could be exposed to health problems that range from Hepatitis C to HIV (Dumont et al., 2012; Rich, Wakeman, & Dickman, 2011). When they complete their prison sentence, they have trouble reintegrating into communities as the general public have learned that drug users are depraved and dangerous (Bonnie & Whitebread, 1974; Pratt, 2009; Walker, 1981). Due to financial constraints in maintaining relationships with family and the length of time individuals remain in prison, many people will have a lack o f supportive networks once they leave prison (Schwartz-Soicher, Geller, & Garfinkel, 2011). Those who have been to prison tend to earn lower wages than those who have not, compounding financial difficulties (Pettit & Lyons, 2009). They may even be a public health hazard in their community by potentially spreading any diseases they incurred while in prison (Dumont et al., 2012). On top o f all this punishment, many people will return to jail because they still use drugs~66.7% of drug users are rearrested for drug charges within 3 years o f release, 51.8% o f which were for simple violations such as failing a drug test (Langan & Levin, 2002).
Impact on public opinion. In recent years, mandatory minimums sentencing has become increasingly unpopular; a variety o f groups, including prisoners, the families of those incarcerated, health officials, judges, and attorneys have been voicing their desire to amend current legislation (ACLU, 2013; Rehnquist, 2005; Rich, Wakeman, & Dickman, 2011; Roberts, Doble, Clawson, Selton, & Briker, 2005; United States Sentencing
42

Commission, 2010). Chief Justice William Rehnquist asserts mandatory minimums have “require[d] huge expenditures” to both build new prisons and house prisoners while also disrupting the balance and efficacy of the corrections system by forcing “too long” mandatory minimum sentences without judiciary discretion (2005, par. 20). In a 2010 study, U.S. District Court judges were asked their opinion on whether statutory sentences were appropriate; 76% agreed the statutes for cocaine offenses were too high (United States Sentencing Commission, 2010). Health professionals argue that current legislation not only fails to address the drug problem or improve public safety, but it has also created new public health issues for those in prison and to the communities to which they, eventually, return (Dumont et al., 2012; Rich, Wakeman, & Dickman, 2011). Even Ed Meese, the former U.S. Attorney General under President Reagan believes “mandatory minimums for drug offenders ought to be reviewed” (2010, par. 6).
Regardless of political and racial backgrounds, the public oppose mandatory minimums. In a 2005 Massachusetts study, 76% of people surveyed—who still agree that drugs are America’s top social problem—believe there should be discretion in sentencing terms (Roberts, Doble, Clawson, Selton, & Briker, 2005). A Gallup, Inc. poll in 2012 showed only 31% of those surveyed thought we had made progress in the nation’s efforts on drugs in recent years.
There are also numerous political and advocacy groups that are currently working to repeal mandatory minimum sentencing. The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) is a group made up of attorneys and criminal justice professionals that seeks to ensure the rights of marginalized people, including people of color, people with disabilities, LGBT
43

individuals, women, and prisoners. One of their key issues is to amend unjust drug sentencing and penalties for crack cocaine users. They disseminate free information to the public to increase awareness of the issues related to drug sentencing and use their position to challenge discriminatory legislation and advocate for the needs of those incarcerated (ACLU, 2013). Section C: Implication of the Policy for the Operating and Outcome Variables of Social
Policies By 1993, three times the previous allocations were needed to provide for the rapidly rising prison population (Simon, 1993). Those with mandatory minimum penalties serve a sentence that is on average 20% longer than it would have been without the imposed minimum (Vincent & Hoffer, 1994), and more prison space would be needed to accommodate for more violators spending longer time in prison. From 1980 to 1996, prison bed space increased from 24,094 to 76,442 to accommodate for additional bodies (National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse, 1998). As the prison population continued to grow over the years after this policy’s implementation (Clark, 1994; Glaze, 2010; Katel, 2007), the federal government needed to adjust its resources to adjust to the change. From 1980 to 1996, the building and operational costs o f prisons and jails increased 443% from $7 billion to $38 billion annually; bed space in prison increased from 24,094 to 76,442 (National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse, 1998). Of these costs, 80% were attributed to costs for incarcerating those with substance-related charges (National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse, 1998). A new industry of private prisons grew to manage the overflow of the federal prison population (Quinlan, Thomas, & Gautreaux, 2001). This, in itself,
44

has created a new set o f ethical questions on the role of a third party agency to conduct the not-for-profit task to oversee the “corrections” o f offenders when they are a for-profit group (Quinlan, Thomas, & Gautreaux, 2001).
While funding changes meant more money was going into the criminal justice system, there were other areas that received less funding because of this policy shift. Currently, the average annual cost per inmate is $26,359; federal incarcerations require a $5.7 billion dollar budget (Federal Bureau of Prisons, 2012). Community and public mental health operations, that had previously been the agencies to address drug prevalence, received less funding after the 1980s (Pratt, 2009). In 1989, only 8% of regular users received drug treatment in prison (National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse, 1998).
This policy has also changed the rights and responsibilities of several groups. First, it has changed the rights ofjudges. They no longer have the ability to exercise sentencing discretion since the policy outlines and requires mandatory minimum sentences (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). Several judges express criticisms towards this requirement. For example, Chief Justice Rehnquist feel punishments are “unduly harsh for first-time offenders” (2005, par. 20). U.S. District Judge Paul Cassell agrees punishments are “unjust, cruel, and irrational” for first-time offenders” (2004, par. 24). However, due to this policy, judges are obligated to impose mandatory minimum sentences, regardless of their perspective of the verdict after hearing the details of the case.
45

Summary The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 was written with the intent to address crime and a high drug prevalence in the United States (Reagan, 1986a). Policy-makers intended to do this by incarcerating drug users for a minimum sentence of 5 to 20 years (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). However, the impact of mandatory minimum sentencing has been to inequitably disadvantage women, people of color, and low-income communities (Alexander, 2010; Lenora, Luthra, Verma, Small, Allard, & Levingston, 2005; Mauer & King, 2007; Vagins & McCurdy, 2006). As a result of mass incarcerations that have happened within these communities, our prison populations have sky-rocketed to all time highs (Clark, 1994; Glaze, 2010; Katel, 2007; National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse, 1998). Those who go to prison for long periods of time are more subject to health risks and social detriments when they are released from prison (Rich, Wakeman, & Dickman, 2011; Dumont et al., 2012). The communities of those left behind also suffer and fall into further economic despair when many individuals are removed from their communities and incarcerated for long periods of time (Alexander, 2010; Pratt, 2009).
46

CHAPTER 5 SUMMARY AND CONCLUSIONS The purpose of this study was to conduct a policy analysis of the effects of mandatory minimum sentencing as outlined in the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986. A modified version of David Gil’s 1992 framework was used to analyze the policy’s purpose, goals, implementation, and impacts.
Summary of Findings The aim of the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 was to reduce the high prevalence of drugs and drug-related violent crime in the United States. The first title within the policy, the Narcotics Penalties and Enforcement Act, directly amended the Controlled Substances Act o f 1970 and employed mandatory minimum sentences for those who were caught in possession of illegal drugs (Anti-Drug Abuse Act, 1986). The dangers of drugs on society has been a common discussion since the turn of the twentieth century (Kefamer Committee Hearings, 1981; Reagan, 1986a). For a hundred years, American policy has alternated between supply-reduction and demandreduction philosophies on how to address drug use (Hawdon, 2001; Lynch, 2012). During the 1980s, the prevalent approach to reducing drug use relied upon incarcerating those in possession of drugs, isolating them from society where they can potentially cause harm (Hawdon, 2001; Reagan, 1986a). The Anti-Drug Abuse Act o f 1986 emulated this philosophy by incarcerating those in possession o f drugs for lengthly sentences that
47

ranged from 5 to 20 years, minimum. Yet research suggests that mandatory minimums have not played a significant role
in reducing the prevalence o f drugs nor the incidence of drug-related violent crime. Research suggests the concern of high prevalence of drug use in the 1980s had been largely over-exaggerated by the media (Beckett, 1994; Orcutt & Turner, 1993; Reeves & Campbell, 1994). Statistics from the same period suggest drug-related crime is not all that common when reviewing crime rates (Dorsey & Middleton, 2005; Spiess & Fallow, 2000; Timrots & Byrne, 1995).
Additionally, mandatory minimums have caused new social problems to emerge. Due to lengthy sentences, the prison population has burgeoned (Katel, 2007). This has come at a great financial cost to taxpayers to cover related costs for prisoners (Federal Bureau o f Prisons, 2012). It also comes at a great social cost as prison overcrowding directly contributes to poor health and potential spread o f diseases between offenders who are incarcerated from this policy; this also increases the odds of spreading illnesses into the communities to which they return (Dumont et al., 2012; Rich, Wakeman, & Dickman, 2011).
Mandatory minimums have also exacerbated existing social problems of sexism, racism, and related disparities. Women have been disproportionately affected by mandatory minimum sentences (Lenora, Luthra, Verma, Small, Allard, & Levingston, 2005). There is a significant amount of African Americans who have been incarcerated, disproportionately to Caucasians (Alexander, 2010; Dumont, Brockmann, Dickman, Alexander, & Rich, 2012; National Center for Health Statistics, 2012; Smith & Hattery,
48

2010). As a result of mass incarcerations, communities of color are facing increased
socioeconomic hardships (Alexander, 2010; Finzen, 2005; Smith & Hattery, 2010). After incarceration, it is harder for ex-convicts to receive a job because o f their criminal records (Holzer, 1996; Kling, 2007). It may be hard to obtain the skills necessary for a job due to imprisonment during prime education and skill-development years (Justice Policy Institute, 2002; Kling, 2007). This decreases opportunities for economic advancement for those who have been incarcerated (Kling, 2007). Welfare assistance for those who are struggling financially can also be withheld and denied based off an offender’s past criminal record (Personal Responsibility and Work Opportunity Reconciliation Act, 1996). Those who are incarcerated are facing economic discrimination in a way that will likely negatively impact their and their communities quality o f life for many years and generations (Finzen, 2005).
Policies developed after the shift towards punitive, supply-reduction policy have influenced and aided the passage of additional punitive, supply-reduction policies that continued to impact those who use drugs. Policies passed since the Anti-Drug Abuse Act have continued to punish drug offenders even after they have served prison time. For example, due to policy regulations, those who have received mandatory minimum sentences would be restricted from receiving benefits (Personal Responsibility and Work Opportunity Reconciliation Act, 1996). Those with felonies also cannot advocate for themselves politically as their right to vote is restricted in multiple states (Alexander, 2010; Dumont et al., 2012). These examples demonstrate how additional policies have
49

been designed in a way that encroach upon the rights of those who have been convicted o f drug charges by restricting their equal access to goods and services even after they have completed their sentences.
These efforts to better address drug prevalence will hopefully have several effects. First, it will end the discriminatory practices that have happened in connection to the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986. Second, it will offer opportunities to better address drug use and prevalence in America. Third, candid discussions regarding drug use as a public health issue can potentially end stigma and misunderstandings that perpetrate continuous criminalization of previous offenders.
Implications for Future Research Further research could explore several areas. First, the criminal justice system could benefit from evidence-based research on how to be more effective. This would most likely include a study o f international correctional systems to see how other countries, similar to ours, have affectively addressed problematic drug use. Additional research should review and compare how other countries have treated drug use differently outside of the corrections system. Americans may benefit from research that explores a distinction between simple or recreational drug use and problematic drug use. There may be a distinction between the two categories. If so, future policies can be created that address problematic drug use. As these policies will hopefully include provisions for evidence-based treatment of substance use, further research could also be study effective treatment o f problematic drug use. Current research suggests re-entry programs that offer employment, housing,
50

and social supports are integral in reducing recidivism and supporting a successful re­ entry into the general community (Gideon, 2009). Further research could explore new ways to make such programs more accessible and effective with those who use substances; it can also explore the efficacy of such programs in reducing problematic substance use.
Implications for Social Work Practice and Policy Social workers can learn several important lessons from a review of mandatory minimums. First, we can learn the importance of evidence-based practice in policy. As learned from the Boggs Act of 1951, mandatory minimums had a history o f being ineffective (Mascharka, 2000). Regardless, the harshest penalties in American history were still enacted with the passing of the Anti-Drug Abuse Act. A core value in social work is competence (National Association of Social Workers, 1999). To better advance competence in policy development, social workers can do several things. They can educate the public on the true nature of drug use in this country, encouraging Americans to consider the difference between recreational drug use and problematic drug use. They can educate on impacts of this policy on target and nontarget populations, as well the unintended consequences and cost to society. They can also advocate for the removal of discriminatory practices that negatively impact social groups. Finally, social workers can begin to review international efforts to address drug issues. This can offer initial ideas and suggestions for evidence-based treatment of substance use and possession in our own nation through other nation’s efforts. Social workers have a vested interest in concerning themselves with the issues
51

surrounding mandatory minimums. As advocates for social justice, one can determine that it is in the profession’s interest to advocate for the individuals, families, and communities that have been negatively impacted by mandatory minimum sentences.
There are various approaches social workers can employ to address the problems of crime and drug-prevalence. First, we must recognize that the drug prevalence has consistently lowered since 1979 (SAMHSA, 2010; Timrots & Byrne, 1995) and has consistently been at or below 5% for a decade (SAMHSA, 2011). Drug-related crime is also at consistently low rates, regardless ofAmerican fears that drug users will commit crimes to sustain their habits (Dorsey & Middleton, 2007; Mascharka, 2000; Spiess & Fallow, 2000; Vincent & Hofer, 1994). Once this truth is acknowledged, policy-makers and die public may better support policies that reflect the true nature of drug-related issues in America.
To share this message, social workers can take advantage of the media—film, documentaries, newspapers, magazines, social networking, various forms of marketing, and so forth. Use of the media has been used for a hundred years to paint a villainous picture of drug users and their impact on communities. Social workers can take a vested interested in using the media to spread more information about the highly addictive nature of substances and now people who have serious drug addictions need treatment. Human interest stories can profile the journey that substance users go through in order to build empathy and understanding to the systematic reasons why people use drugs. The media can also be used to provide examples and opportunities for the public to gain more education on drug issues and how to address drug issues. Social workers can learn the
52

importance that the media plays in the public’s perception of social issues. The general public’s opinion can greatly impact the direction o f public policy; politicians can decide to push a piece of legislation if they feel they will be viewed better in the eyes of their constituents. Journalistic articles and news reports appear to have a great impact on the public’s opinion o f social issues. Therefore, social workers should take it upon themselves to educate ourselves on the issues, and then disseminate information to the public about the truth o f mandatory minimums. Furthermore, they should also spread information regarding evidence-based practices to address drug use in the media. If advocacy groups, including social workers and other vested parties, take intentional efforts to inform the general public, they will have more information available to themselves to know how to vote and further discuss issues around drug use and related crime.
Recent years have seen a resurgence of therapeutic and demand-reduction policies. In 2000, California passed Proposition 36 which allows low-level offenders treatment in lieu of serving time for drug violations (Substance Abuse Crime and Prevention Act, 2000). This legislation that echoes of the Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act of 1970 which also allowed treatment alternatives to prison time. Future policies could benefit from employing a therapeutic, demand-reduction approach to addressing problematic drug use in America, considering treatment and rehabilitative options in lieu of prison. However, there are still ethical considerations in offering treatment as opposed to incarceration. If the individual does not truly desire to stop using drugs, he or she can complete the treatment and return to previous habits. This
53

likely has the option to have these individuals return to court for drug possession. A second drug offense contains harsher penalties and will likely be viewed with a more critical eye as the offender has been to court for the same crime. The ethical question remains on whether or not forced treatment options, while keeping the individual out of prison, set the individual up for failure. The fact that many people who have gone through drug courts and wound up going to prison for a similar crime suggests they may be less than effective (Lynch, 2012).
Other cultures have already begun implementing alternative strategies that address problematic drug use without incarcerating for every single crime. The Netherlands is often looked to as an example of a country that allows some drugs to be regulated. For example, it is legal to sell or use five grams or less of marijuana (Holland, 2013). However, many do not realize that the nation’s official stance on drug use is to “reduce the demand for drugs, die supply o f drugs and the risks to drug users, their immediate surroundings and society” (Holland, 2013, par. 4). They, however, believe the best way to meet this goal is not necessarily to eliminate drugs altogether, but to employ a harm reduction philosophy (Holland, 2013; van Laar et al., 2010). Rather than focusing on supply or demand reduction, harm reduction focuses instead on ways to decrease the harmful affects of drug use on personal and public health by examining and improving the social and physical disposition o f users (Leuw & Marshall, 1994). A comparison of prevalence rates between the Netherlands and America suggests that the Netherlands prevalence is lower than America’s; in America, marijuana, cocaine, hallucinogens, and other psychotherapeutic drugs had respective monthly prevalence rates of 6.9%, .9% ,.

5%, and 2.7% (SAMHSA, 2010). In the Netherlands, the rates for marijuana, cocaine, ecstasy, and amphetamines, LSD, and heroin were respectively 5.%, .6%, 1.2%, an d . 3%, .1%, and 0% (van Laar et al., 2010). In 2009, there were 6.527 drug-related crimes identified in the nation, 50% o f which were property crimes without violence (van Laar et al., 2010).
From the Netherlands, we can learn two lessons for future policy development. First, we can learn that not all drug use needs to be treated with punitive criminal justice policies. With less strict sentencing guidelines, the Netherlands has managed to have a comparable, even slightly improved, drug prevalence rate (SAMHSA, 2010; van Laar et al., 2010). Perhaps future policies can potentially restrict lengthy sentences to those who truly have commit violent crime, not to all those who have the potential to commit violent crime because they use illegal substances. We can also learn the philosophy o f the harm reduction model which treats drug use as a public health issue instead o f a criminal justice issue. In light of this, future policies may better reflect harm reduction model, focusing on strategic ways to reduce the problems associated with drug use.
Some approaches have taken a truly preventative approach to addressing rising drug use in communities. In Gary, Indiana, citizens noticed a rising problem with drug prevalence and examined the changes in the community to explore why drug use was increasing. They related the problem back to the fact that jobs had been leaving the town and economic opportunities were decreasing. An interfaith network sought to address this by campaigning for an affordable public transit system that would enable more residents to access gainful employment. The effects were noticeable; drug use decreased
55

and more residents became gainfully employed (Pastor, Benner, & Matsuoka, 2009). It is the focus on preventative measures that may prove to be the most useful
tactic in reducing problematic drug use in America. Like the Netherlands, we may determine that possession under a predetermined threshold may be spared punitive measures. For areas that had a concentrated drug prevalence, we may take the example of Gary, Indiana, and conduct a needs assessment to assess the underlying factors to problematic drug use. With the gathered information, a potential solution may be offered in conjunction with the state and other community partners to address the underlying issues that caused problematic substance use in the community to flourish. If it proves effective, this could reduce the problems associated with sending individuals to prison and the impacts that has on die person, the family, and the community left behind.
